%%TITLE
Prognostic value of p16 expression irrespective of human papillomavirus status in patients with oropharyngeal carcinoma.
%%ABSTRACT
In a previous study, we reported the value of p16 expression and alcohol consumption in oropharyngeal carcinoma in Japan. We now report the clinical significance of human papillomavirus status and p16 expression in oropharyngeal carcinoma in Japan.Over a 9-year period, a retrospective case comparison study of the pathology database was conducted at the University of Tokyo to identify tumor samples of oropharyngeal carcinoma. We performed immunohistochemistry for the p16 protein, in situ hybridization for human papillomavirus-deoxyribonucleic acid and polymerase chain reaction for the human papillomavirus-deoxyribonucleic acid oncogene E6 in oropharyngeal carcinoma in Japanese patients. We evaluated the human papillomavirus status in patients with oropharyngeal carcinoma to determine its prevalence and association with prognosis. We defined human papillomavirus(+) and human papillomavirus(-) oropharyngeal carcinoma cohorts as those with and without polymerase chain reaction for the human papillomavirus-deoxyribonucleic acid oncogene E6 or in situ hybridization-human papillomavirus.In oropharyngeal carcinoma, the prevalences of p16(+)human papillomavirus(+), p16(+)human papillomavirus(-), p16(-)human papillomavirus(+) and p16(-)human papillomavirus(-) were 32% (48/150), 7% (10/150), 2% (3/150) and 59% (89/150), respectively. Low tobacco and alcohol consumption, tonsil or base of tongue localization, but not age, were associated with p16(+)human papillomavirus(+). Low alcohol consumption was associated with p16(+)human papillomavirus(-). There was a significant difference in overall survival between p16(+)human papillomavirus(-) and p16(-)human papillomavirus(-) (P = 0.03). In multivariate Cox regression models, p16 was the independent prognostic factor, regardless of human papillomavirus status.p16 expression was a reliable prognostic biomarker regardless of human papillomavirus status.
%%PATIENTS AND METHODS
Between January 2004 and December 2012, we enrolled 167 patients with OPSCC treated with curative intent in the Department of Otolaryngology and Head and Neck Surgery, Tokyo University, Tokyo, Japan. We excluded 17 patients receiving palliative treatment due to poor performance status and those with poor quality histo- logical samples. The clinical charts of the remaining 150 patients were reviewed. Sixty-three patients (42%) underwent primary curative surgery, of these 10 were treated with post-operative radiotherapy (PORT) on the basis of pathological risk factors. Thirty-one patients (21%) underwent chemoradiation therapy (CRT) and 56 patients (37%) underwent radiotherapy (RT). Cisplatin-based induction chemotherapy has been recently indicated for some cases of Stage III and IV disease, and it was decided that good responders should be treated with RT instead of surgery. We included the patients with in- duction chemotherapy subsequent RT and surgery into RT group and surgery group, respectively. None of the treatments were influenced by
p16 or HPV status until 2011 when these markers were introduced for routine use at our institution. The TNM staging system was used to classify the tumors in accordance with the American Joint Committee on Cancer classification. Formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) pre-treatment biopsies were retrieved from the records of our Depart- ment of Pathology. The Institutional Review Board approved the protocol for this study, and written informed consent was obtained from all patients before enrollment.
Immunohistochemistry
We performed p16 immunostaining on representative 4 µm sections cut from FFPE tissue blocks obtained prior to chemotherapy or radio- therapy. Deparaffinized sections were autoclaved for 20 min in Target Retrieval Solution (S1700; Dako Japan Inc., Tokyo, Japan) for antigen retrieval. Mouse anti-p16 monoclonal antibody (Santa Cruz Biotech- nology, Inc., Santa Cruz, CA, USA; dilution 1:100) was used as the primary antibody and incubated overnight at 4°C. Histofine® Simple Stain MAX-PO (M) was used as the secondary antibody (Nichirei Corp, Tokyo, Japan), according to the manufacturer’s instructions. The tissue sections were counterstained with hematoxylin. The case of HPV-positive oropharyngeal carcinoma with diffuse and strong im- munoreaction of p16 (not enrolled in this study) was used as a positive control, and the section of the specific normal tonsil which showed no immunoreaction of p16 was used as a negative control. The p16 immunohistochemistry (IHC) was considered positive if strong diffuse staining was noted in the nucleus and cytoplasm of >70% of the malignant cells.
Detection of HPV-DNA using in situ hybridization (ISH-HPV)
HPV-DNA was detected in FFPE blocks using a catalyzed signal amp- lification ISH method (GenPoint signal amplification system for bioti- nylated probes; Dako Japan Inc.) for all 150 tumors. After 4 µm sections were deparaffinized and underwent heat-induced target re- trieval with S1700 in citrate buffer, and digestion using Proteinase K (Dako Japan Inc.). Slides were then hybridized using a biotinylated GenPoint™ HPV probe (this probe has been found to react with HPV types 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59 and 68 on
FFPE tissues and/or cells by in situ hybridization, Dako Japan Inc.). After initial binding of the streptavidin–horseradish peroxidase com- plex to the probe, signal amplification was performed using biotinyl tyramide. Positive hybridization signals were visualized by adding the chromogenic substrate diaminobenzidine. The case of HPV-positive oropharyngeal carcinoma (not enrolled in this study) was used as a positive control. Slides were scored as positive for HPV if a punctate signal pattern was observed in the tumor cell nuclei.
Detection of HPV-16 DNA using PCR (PCR-E6) FFPE tissue sections were assessed by a pathologist for tumor diagno- sis; then, DNA was extracted using a Qiagen QIAamp DNABlood mini kit (Qiagen, Valencia, CA, USA) for p16-positive 55 tumors. The presence of HPV was examined using real-time PCR to generate amplified DNA fragments within the open reading frames of E6. The primers for the E6 open reading frame included the sense primer 5′-GAACTGCAATGTTTCAGGACCC-3′ (nucleotide position 26– 47), and the antisense primer, 5′-ATATACCTCACGTCGCAGTAA CTGTT-3′ (nucleotide position 210–232) (). The 50 µl PCR reaction buffer consisted of 5 µl of template DNA, a 5 µmol/l concentration of each sense and antisense primer, a 2-µmol/l concentration of the TaqMan® probe (Applied Biosystems, Tokyo, Japan), and 25 µl of
the TaqMan® Universal PCR Master Mix (Applied Biosystems). The amplification conditions were 2 min at 50°C and 15 min at 95°C, followed by a two-step cycle of 94°C for 15 s and 60°C for 30 s, for a total of 50 cycles. The samples were considered positive when the E6 copy number per nanogram DNA was equal to or greater than the number obtained from the HPV-16-positive OPSCC tissues (not enrolled in this study).
Alcohol and tobacco consumption All patients were interviewed about their smoking and drinking habits during their first medical examination at our department. The ques- tionnaire requested information on the daily amounts and overall durations of tobacco smoking and alcohol consumption, as well as the preferred type of alcoholic beverage. The total number of pack- years (one pack year is defined as 20 cigarettes smoked per day for 1 year) and the total alcohol consumption (one drink = 14 g alcohol) were then calculated. Tobacco smokers were defined as individuals who had smoked for 20 pack-years (i.e. >1 pack per day for 20 years), and alcohol users were defined as individuals who had a history of heavy alcohol consumption (15 drinks/week for 15 years).
Statistical analysis
Potential relationships between p16 expression and HPV positivity were tested using the χ2 test. Univariate comparison of patient charac- teristics between groups was performed using either the χ2 test or the Fisher’s exact test for qualitative variables, and either the Student t-test or the non-parametric Mann–Whitney U test for quantitative variables, as appropriate.
The primary endpoint of the study was overall survival (OS); univariate OS was evaluated using the Kaplan–Meier method and the log-rank test. Variables were also analyzed using multivariate survival analysis using a Cox proportional hazard model. The hazard ratio (HR) and 95% confidence interval (CI) were calculated to deter- mine the effect of each variable on the outcome with an HR < 1.0. P values <0.05 were considered statistically significant. All analyses were carried out using Microsoft Excel version 2010 (Microsoft, Redmond, WA, USA) and StatFlex version 6.0 (Artech Co, Ltd).
